        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>From Bolatto et al, The peak detection of CI towards N27 has a brightness of 14 mK, with a 228" beam, and line width 9.3 (+/- 3.3) km/s.
Mizuno et al (in prep) report a peak brightness of about 0.4 K, with the NANTEN2 telescope (beam is 38”), and a line width of about 2.1 km/s
N27 is known to have multiple components (e.g. Nikolic et al, 2007), which would be blended by the large beam of AST/RO, we therefore use the results from Mizuno et al. to compute a more conservative required sensitivity.
To remove the effects of beam dilution, we scale to estimate the peak flux considering the maximum resolvable scale in band 8, which is about 5 arcseconds, with a beam dilution factor of: (38/5)^2 = 58. We expect then, a minimum peak brightness of about 23 K.
We wish to resolve the quarter power point of the edges of the emission regions to an S/N of 5, thus, we calculate for a conservative sensitivity of 23/20. ~  1 K.
Mizuno et al (in prep), et al find a velocity width of approximately 2.1 km/s. ALMA’s finer beam will disentangle any disparate clouds with slightly different systemic velocities that are conflated by the NANTEN2 beam, and we expect to detect narrower widths with resolved observations (as Mizuno et al already show, with a width of 2.1 km/s with a 38” beam vs. the 9.1 km/s from the 228” AST/RO beam). We configure the frequnency setup to achive the maximum resolution possible, but make our sensitivity computations to take into account: a factor of 5 decrease in velocity width (a comparable ratio to the reduction in linewidths with scale, based on Mizuno et al, and Bolatto et al, 2000), and a factor of three to appropriately resolve the lines - in total, we make our sensitivity computations for 2.1/5x3 = 0.14 km/s
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
