    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose observations to address a very-long standing question: is the observed CO under-luminosity a result of enhanced photo-ionisation, resulting from the enhanced penetration by UV in the low-metalicity and dust-poor SMC ISM?
The notoriously low CO luminosity in the SMC is, since the earliest surveys by the SEST Key projects, well established. The reason for the low luminosity is not. The reason may be simple: the high transparency of the SMC ISM, being dust-poor, may permit a more penetrating photo-disassociation of the CO - converting CO to CI. 
Our project will measure directly, on scales as-yet unobserved in the Magellanic system, the distribution of ionised carbon in the context of the neutral CO (from existing data, and Cycle 2 proposals), the dust (traced by the continuum). Is the CI present? is it smoothly distributed, or is it correlated with the neutral CO, or the dust temperature/density? In any case, we will be able to make enormous steps towards understanding some very fundamental parameters that could have far reaching implications for understanding the evolution of molecular clouds, and star formation, in all low-metallicity systems.</prp:abstract>
